1
00:00:48,088 --> 00:00:50,477
- <i>(laughter)</i>
- <i>(man)</i> OK, alright, hold up.

2
00:00:50,568 --> 00:00:54,007
Someone has to say something
nice about my friend Herb tonight,

3
00:00:54,088 --> 00:00:56,477
so I'm gonna give it a shot.

4
00:00:56,568 --> 00:00:59,924
I have followed Herb Lee
my whole writing career.

5
00:01:00,008 --> 00:01:04,365
I followed him through three publishing
houses, and when he started his own.

6
00:01:04,448 --> 00:01:09,363
It's embarrassing to need your editor
so badly, so I'm gratified to announce

7
00:01:09,448 --> 00:01:13,202
that he has now followed me
to Central Connecticut. Thank you.

8
00:01:13,288 --> 00:01:15,643
I didn't follow you,
I had three heart attacks.

9
00:01:15,728 --> 00:01:18,367
This was a pre-emptive strike
against decrepitude.

10
00:01:18,448 --> 00:01:21,008
- <i>(laughter)</i>
- Well, whatever brought you here

11
00:01:21,088 --> 00:01:23,727
to the beautiful
Marigold Retirement Community,

12
00:01:23,808 --> 00:01:27,437
I just want to say I'm glad you're here,
right down the road from my place,

13
00:01:27,528 --> 00:01:30,759
and as long as Pippa
keeps making that butterflied lamb,

14
00:01:30,848 --> 00:01:33,157
I'll do anything.
I'll even caddy for you.

15
00:01:33,248 --> 00:01:35,808
That's fine,
as long as I don't have to play golf.

16
00:01:35,888 --> 00:01:38,846
Wait, one more thing.
I just want to say something else.

17
00:01:38,928 --> 00:01:41,761
I have known Pippa Lee for 25 years...

18
00:01:42,848 --> 00:01:45,840
<i>...and</i> I think
that I will never really know her.

19
00:01:45,928 --> 00:01:49,204
She is a mystery. An enigma.

20
00:01:49,288 --> 00:01:54,646
Giving, caring, beautiful, intelligent,

21
00:01:54,728 --> 00:01:57,162
the very icon of an artist's wife.

22
00:01:57,248 --> 00:02:00,126
- What are you talking about?
- No, you are.

23
00:02:00,208 --> 00:02:03,280
And who precisely is this artist
that Pippa is married to?

24
00:02:03,368 --> 00:02:05,359
- <i>(laughter)</i>
- Exactly!

25
00:02:05,448 --> 00:02:08,087
Yes, that's my point!
That's what it's come down to.

26
00:02:08,168 --> 00:02:11,160
The one true artist's wife
left in the modern world,

27
00:02:11,248 --> 00:02:13,239
and she ended up with a publisher.

28
00:02:13,328 --> 00:02:16,638
To Herb and Pippa
and their weird new condo.

29
00:02:16,728 --> 00:02:20,084
Yeah, I just, er, got three new poems.

30
00:02:20,168 --> 00:02:24,366
Wonderful. If you'd ever like to show
them to somebody who's non-judgemental,

31
00:02:24,448 --> 00:02:26,757
- I'd be happy to take a look at them.
- Really?

32
00:02:26,848 --> 00:02:29,840
I would like that.
That would mean so much to me.

33
00:02:29,928 --> 00:02:32,920
I wish Sam wouldn't keep saying
Daddy moved to be near him.

34
00:02:33,008 --> 00:02:36,796
He's a satirist. Anyway, nothing's
going to put a dent in Herb's ego.

35
00:02:36,888 --> 00:02:38,879
It's you I'm worried about.

36
00:02:40,528 --> 00:02:42,166
It's time for dessert.

37
00:02:42,248 --> 00:02:45,843
But, Herb, what is the real reason
you moved here?

38
00:02:45,928 --> 00:02:48,237
Scaling down, making life more simple.

39
00:02:48,328 --> 00:02:51,320
I've liquidated everything
so that when I go,

40
00:02:51,408 --> 00:02:54,878
Pippa and the kids can get everything
and not give it to the government.

41
00:02:54,968 --> 00:02:57,277
<i>(Sam)</i> I thought you loved paying taxes.

42
00:02:57,368 --> 00:03:00,519
I have to admit, I actually like
this house. It's so easy.

43
00:03:00,608 --> 00:03:02,883
I'm glad you feel that way, sweetie.

44
00:03:03,728 --> 00:03:06,925
Though I can't help wondering
how many people have died here.

45
00:03:07,008 --> 00:03:11,286
Your problem is you're too adaptable.
You're the adaptable enigma.

46
00:03:15,608 --> 00:03:19,760
<i>(Pippa) To be perfectly honest,</i>
<i>I've had enough of being an enigma.</i>

47
00:03:23,968 --> 00:03:25,959
<i>I wanna be known.</i>

48
00:03:31,808 --> 00:03:35,084
<i>Like many people,</i>
<i>I have lived more than one life,</i>

49
00:03:35,168 --> 00:03:37,728
<i>so we're going to have to start</i>
<i>at the beginning.</i>

50
00:03:37,808 --> 00:03:40,481
- <i>(man)</i> Breathe. Breathe.
- <i>(woman)</i> Shut up!

51
00:03:41,688 --> 00:03:44,202
I see the head. Come on, one good push!

52
00:03:44,288 --> 00:03:46,643
<i>(yells)</i> Oh, fuck you!

53
00:03:46,728 --> 00:03:48,878
- <i>(baby cries)</i>
- <i>(man)</i> Good girl.

54
00:03:48,968 --> 00:03:52,199
<i>My birth was marked</i>
<i>by several unusual occurrences.</i>

55
00:03:52,288 --> 00:03:55,678
<i>First of all,</i>
<i>I was covered in fine blonde fur.</i>

56
00:03:55,768 --> 00:03:57,759
<i>(baby cries)</i>

57
00:03:57,848 --> 00:04:00,601
- Why is she furry?
- That's nothing to worry about.

58
00:04:00,688 --> 00:04:03,760
When a baby's this late,
it has time to grow vestigial hair,

59
00:04:03,848 --> 00:04:05,679
from the time that we were monkeys.

60
00:04:06,488 --> 00:04:10,720
I had a monkey! I had a monkey!

61
00:04:10,808 --> 00:04:13,527
You can expect to have
a beautiful baby girl.

62
00:04:13,608 --> 00:04:16,566
The hair is just vestigial,
as I tried to tell your wife.

63
00:04:16,648 --> 00:04:20,800
I'm sorry if it offends you, Father, but
we believe that millions of years ago,

64
00:04:20,888 --> 00:04:23,356
- humans were covered with fur.
- I know that.

65
00:04:23,448 --> 00:04:25,678
So, is it a baby or a pet?

66
00:04:25,768 --> 00:04:29,477
<i>Suky knew my condition</i>
<i>had nothing to do with evolution.</i>

67
00:04:29,568 --> 00:04:33,720
<i>It was all her fault,</i>
<i>because my mother had a secret,</i>

68
00:04:33,808 --> 00:04:36,686
<i>her own little stash of sin.</i>

69
00:04:36,768 --> 00:04:38,998
<i>(whistles)</i>

70
00:04:42,488 --> 00:04:45,446
- How's my pal?
- I'm OK.

71
00:04:47,208 --> 00:04:50,245
Are you having a hard time
living here in Wrinkleberry?

72
00:04:50,328 --> 00:04:55,118
It's strange having so much time on my
hands. This place is easy to maintain,

73
00:04:55,208 --> 00:04:57,847
but there's gonna be charity work
I can find.

74
00:04:57,928 --> 00:05:01,159
- You wanna move back to the city?
- We just sold our apartment.

75
00:05:01,248 --> 00:05:04,524
- Well, we can get another one.
- Are you serious?

76
00:05:04,608 --> 00:05:06,246
No.

77
00:05:07,328 --> 00:05:11,719
I'm just having a hard time
thinking of this as the end of the line.

78
00:05:14,728 --> 00:05:20,086
I think it's sort of romantic...
starting all over, just the two of us.

79
00:05:20,168 --> 00:05:21,760
So little stuff.

80
00:05:21,848 --> 00:05:24,840
Must you always look at the bright side?

81
00:05:27,968 --> 00:05:30,084
Can I get you anything?

82
00:05:30,168 --> 00:05:33,365
- Some carrot juice?
- No, I'm fine.

83
00:05:38,448 --> 00:05:41,121
What was that cheese
we had for lunch yesterday?

84
00:05:41,208 --> 00:05:45,406
It was vacherin. I was so excited
to find that at the market.

85
00:05:45,488 --> 00:05:47,479
I love that cheese.

86
00:05:59,088 --> 00:06:01,921
<i>Once I lost my furry coat,</i>
<i>my mother was so relieved</i>

87
00:06:02,008 --> 00:06:05,205
<i>that she became sort of obsessed</i>
<i>with my appearance.</i>

88
00:06:05,288 --> 00:06:07,802
<i>She even took a drawing course</i>
<i>at the town hall,</i>

89
00:06:07,888 --> 00:06:10,721
<i>the sole purpose of which</i>
<i>was making pictures of me.</i>

90
00:06:10,808 --> 00:06:14,198
Sweetheart,
you have the most beautiful eyes.

91
00:06:14,288 --> 00:06:18,042
I think God took all of our best
features and put them on your face.

92
00:06:18,128 --> 00:06:20,881
Don't you move. Almost done.

93
00:06:22,288 --> 00:06:24,279
<i>(slams phone down)</i>

94
00:06:26,408 --> 00:06:30,367
Why, you little...
Turkey, turkey, turkey, turkey.

95
00:06:30,448 --> 00:06:31,961
- Ouch!
- <i>(slaps Pippa)</i>

96
00:06:32,048 --> 00:06:34,403
<i>("Teen Baby" by Gary Trexler)</i>

97
00:06:34,488 --> 00:06:38,242
<i>She dressed me up as angels,</i>
<i>cowgirls, movie stars.</i>

98
00:06:39,728 --> 00:06:41,798
<i>I was her prize possession.</i>

99
00:06:41,888 --> 00:06:44,356
<i># You're real, real cool</i>

100
00:06:44,448 --> 00:06:46,006
<i># For you I'm a fool</i>

101
00:06:46,968 --> 00:06:49,436
- <i># Teen baby, be mine</i>
- <i># Honey, I will</i>

102
00:06:49,528 --> 00:06:53,157
- <i># Teen baby, be mine</i>
- <i># Honey, you know I will</i>

103
00:06:53,248 --> 00:06:55,079
<i># Baby, be mine</i>

104
00:06:55,768 --> 00:06:57,679
<i># All of the time</i>

105
00:06:58,328 --> 00:07:00,046
<i># Oh, don't you know</i>

106
00:07:00,888 --> 00:07:02,480
<i># I love you so</i>

107
00:07:03,368 --> 00:07:05,757
- <i># Glad you're my date</i>
- <i># Do-do, do-do-do</i>

108
00:07:05,848 --> 00:07:08,316
<i># With me, you're great</i>
<i>Teen baby, be mine</i>

109
00:07:08,408 --> 00:07:10,399
<i>(gasps)</i>

110
00:07:26,208 --> 00:07:28,676
<i>(police siren)</i>

111
00:07:33,688 --> 00:07:37,840
- <i>(Herb)</i> Who else has a key?
- The cleaning lady.

112
00:07:40,568 --> 00:07:43,844
But I can't see Miss Fanning
breaking in with a few friends

113
00:07:43,928 --> 00:07:46,761
to have chocolate cake
in the middle of the night.

114
00:07:46,848 --> 00:07:49,646
- And the maintenance people?
- You think it was me?

115
00:07:49,728 --> 00:07:54,199
- You think I'm losing my marbles?
- I wasn't saying that. I wasn't...

116
00:07:54,288 --> 00:07:56,279
- Hey.
- There she is.

117
00:07:56,368 --> 00:07:58,438
Hi, Daddy.

118
00:07:58,528 --> 00:08:00,723
- You look great.
- Oh, thanks.

119
00:08:00,808 --> 00:08:03,117
- Hey, Mom.
- Hi.

120
00:08:03,208 --> 00:08:06,359
- I'm starving. Can I get lamb chops?
- Anything you want.

121
00:08:06,448 --> 00:08:09,326
- Do you want a drink first?
- Yeah.

122
00:08:09,408 --> 00:08:12,559
Oh, Ben says, er,
he can't make it until later,

123
00:08:12,648 --> 00:08:15,037
- so we should just order without him.
- OK.

124
00:08:15,128 --> 00:08:18,518
OK, these are just work prints, but...

125
00:08:18,608 --> 00:08:20,997
- Oh, my God.
- You get the idea.

126
00:08:22,528 --> 00:08:26,282
That's incredible. It's amazing, even.

127
00:08:26,368 --> 00:08:29,201
Were you in a doorway? Where were you
when you took this?

128
00:08:29,288 --> 00:08:32,439
Yeah, I just waited there.
I knew they were coming back.

129
00:08:32,528 --> 00:08:35,725
<i>(Herb)</i> That's incredibly powerful.
Look at this.

130
00:08:37,568 --> 00:08:40,002
Oh!

131
00:08:40,088 --> 00:08:43,478
- These are so... powerful.
- These are wonderful.

132
00:08:43,568 --> 00:08:47,641
Grace, this... Hmm.

133
00:08:47,728 --> 00:08:51,437
- Were you alone when you took these?
- No, we had a guide.

134
00:08:51,528 --> 00:08:52,563
You had a guide?

135
00:08:52,648 --> 00:08:55,685
And I hitched a ride with,
erm, Giles Oppenheim.

136
00:08:55,768 --> 00:08:57,440
- With Giles Oppenheim?
- Hm-hmm.

137
00:08:57,528 --> 00:09:00,679
- <i>(Herb)</i> How did you manage that?
- <i>(Grace)</i> He kind of adopted me.

138
00:09:00,768 --> 00:09:04,238
Did you hear about that photographer
that got shot in Baghdad last week?

139
00:09:04,328 --> 00:09:05,761
<i>(Grace)</i> Uh-huh.

140
00:09:05,848 --> 00:09:10,319
<i>(exhales)</i> You heard about the bomb?

141
00:09:10,408 --> 00:09:12,683
- <i>(Grace)</i> Ben, shut up.
- What bomb?

142
00:09:12,768 --> 00:09:14,759
- She was with Oppenheim.
- Ben!

143
00:09:14,848 --> 00:09:18,124
And they heard the <i>whistle. (whistles)</i>

144
00:09:18,208 --> 00:09:21,598
And he wanted to go left,
but she saw an alley towards the right,

145
00:09:21,688 --> 00:09:24,998
and she pulled him towards it,
and that's when the bomb hit.

146
00:09:25,088 --> 00:09:27,238
They turn around,
and if they'd gone left,

147
00:09:27,328 --> 00:09:29,717
they would have been
smashed to smithereens.

148
00:09:29,808 --> 00:09:33,118
- She thinks she's immortal now.
- That's a complete distortion.

149
00:09:33,208 --> 00:09:36,359
- Why can't you ever not say something?
- <i>(Ben)</i> I do not know.

150
00:09:36,448 --> 00:09:40,123
Sweetheart, everybody knows you're
a killer but you gotta be careful.

151
00:09:40,208 --> 00:09:43,484
- You have to use your common sense.
- I do. Dad, look...

152
00:09:43,568 --> 00:09:45,798
There's no way
that I'm not gonna go back.

153
00:09:45,888 --> 00:09:48,721
If you had seen what I saw,
you would feel the same.

154
00:09:48,808 --> 00:09:51,720
You would want to give these people
some dignity.

155
00:09:51,808 --> 00:09:55,198
- <i>(Herb)</i> Just be careful.
- Anyway, I'm going to Baghdad Saturday.

156
00:09:55,288 --> 00:10:01,124
- What's new with you?
- Oh, I found a book. A real cash cow.

157
00:10:01,208 --> 00:10:05,121
<i>(laughs)</i>
Since when do you say "cash cow"?

158
00:10:05,208 --> 00:10:07,961
I never said it
because I never found one before.

159
00:10:08,048 --> 00:10:12,917
- What's it about?
- Oh, it's about war and romance,

160
00:10:13,008 --> 00:10:15,568
- and, er, bad weather.
- Is it good?

161
00:10:15,648 --> 00:10:20,722
A certain kind of good. Highbrow
for lowbrows or lowbrow for highbrows.

162
00:10:20,808 --> 00:10:24,198
Summer reading for people
with multimillion-dollar beach homes.

163
00:10:24,288 --> 00:10:27,598
- Used to be us.
- We still wouldn't have read this book.

164
00:10:27,688 --> 00:10:30,964
<i>(chuckles)</i> So, how are you, Ben?
How is your paper coming?

165
00:10:31,048 --> 00:10:33,118
- <i>(Ben)</i> Fine.
- <i>(Grace)</i> What's it about?

166
00:10:33,208 --> 00:10:35,802
- <i>(Ben)</i> The right to die.
- <i>(Grace)</i> The right to die?

167
00:10:35,888 --> 00:10:40,040
- <i>(Ben)</i> Or the right to kill.
- <i>(voices fade)</i>

168
00:10:40,128 --> 00:10:42,688
<i>("That's All I Want" by Bobby Day)</i>

169
00:10:49,088 --> 00:10:53,081
<i># A sweet little kiss with a wee embrace</i>
<i>A pretty little smile</i>

170
00:10:53,168 --> 00:10:57,446
<i>(Pippa) Suky's energy was unflagging,</i>
<i>day and night.</i>

171
00:11:00,448 --> 00:11:03,724
<i>In spite of</i>
<i>an apparently weak thyroid,</i>

172
00:11:03,808 --> 00:11:06,800
<i>for which she took pills</i>
<i>at seven each morning,</i>

173
00:11:06,888 --> 00:11:12,246
<i>12 noon, and four each afternoon,</i>
<i>I was the only one who knew</i>

174
00:11:12,328 --> 00:11:16,287
<i>that she was secretly pretending</i>
<i>to be in a commercial half the time,</i>

175
00:11:16,368 --> 00:11:18,757
<i>or a movie, and she was the star.</i>

176
00:11:19,928 --> 00:11:26,003
- <i>I thought she was absolutely perfect.</i>
- Mom, can I have some more milk? Mom?

177
00:11:26,088 --> 00:11:30,047
<i>Then there were days when Suky</i>
<i>shorted out,</i>

178
00:11:30,128 --> 00:11:33,200
- <i>like a run-down robot.</i>
- <i>(father)</i> Eat up, kids.

179
00:11:33,288 --> 00:11:36,837
<i>I always felt my real mother</i>
<i>had disappeared in those moments.</i>

180
00:11:36,928 --> 00:11:40,284
<i>It scared me and made me angry.</i>

181
00:11:44,248 --> 00:11:46,716
<i>I thought it must be my fault</i>
<i>that she was sad,</i>

182
00:11:46,808 --> 00:11:49,368
<i>and it was up to me</i>
<i>to make her happy again.</i>

183
00:11:58,888 --> 00:12:02,597
I thought maybe
you forgot to say <i>goodnight. (sniffs)</i>

184
00:12:09,048 --> 00:12:11,164
<i>Her moods ruled my life.</i>

185
00:12:17,528 --> 00:12:20,361
<i>(sighs)</i> My <i>baby. (sniffs)</i>

186
00:12:25,168 --> 00:12:27,557
- <i>(doorbell rings)</i>
- <i>(Pippa)</i> Oh, hello, Dot.

187
00:12:27,648 --> 00:12:31,641
- Would you like some coffee?
- Oh, no, I-I've already had some.

188
00:12:31,728 --> 00:12:34,800
- This is my son, Ben.
- Oh, the lawyer?

189
00:12:34,888 --> 00:12:37,607
<i>(Ben)</i> Not yet. Nice to meet you.

190
00:12:37,688 --> 00:12:40,680
- And Herb. You met Herb.
- Oh, hi, Herb.

191
00:12:40,768 --> 00:12:43,077
<i>(Pippa)</i> Oh, my Lord.

192
00:12:43,168 --> 00:12:48,401
<i>(Dot)</i> That's Mr Swaggart.
He needed to go.

193
00:12:48,488 --> 00:12:50,638
Erm, h-have a seat.

194
00:12:50,728 --> 00:12:53,686
<i>(Dot)</i> You know, there are
other young wives here.

195
00:12:53,768 --> 00:12:56,999
You see them jogging around.

196
00:12:57,088 --> 00:13:01,479
- Is everything OK?
- Well, yes, we're... We're fine.

197
00:13:02,568 --> 00:13:05,844
But my son, erm, Chris...

198
00:13:07,168 --> 00:13:09,602
- In Utah?
- Yes.

199
00:13:09,688 --> 00:13:12,521
He might be coming... east.

200
00:13:12,608 --> 00:13:15,520
Oh, that should be nice,
if they would move near you.

201
00:13:15,608 --> 00:13:20,602
The thing is, he's had some kind
of crisis with his wife, and...

202
00:13:20,688 --> 00:13:23,486
He's left her, and he's...

203
00:13:23,568 --> 00:13:28,483
He's living in his car.
I just don't know what to do.

204
00:13:28,568 --> 00:13:35,041
He was always sort of half baked.
You know what I mean?

205
00:13:38,648 --> 00:13:41,640
You know, it's painful, I know...

206
00:13:43,408 --> 00:13:47,924
<i>...but</i> sometimes you just have to maybe
accept they are who they are.

207
00:13:49,128 --> 00:13:52,279
I mean, I-I feel that with my daughter.

208
00:13:52,368 --> 00:13:54,359
<i>(Dot)</i> You're right.

209
00:13:54,448 --> 00:13:59,886
I knew that I should come to you.
You... I just had a feeling.

210
00:14:01,288 --> 00:14:04,837
- <i>(Ben)</i> He's living in his car?
- Yes, she said he was half baked.

211
00:14:05,848 --> 00:14:08,920
- I wonder what that means.
- It's code. It means halfwit.

212
00:14:09,008 --> 00:14:11,442
- <i>(phone rings)</i>
- Hello?

213
00:14:12,648 --> 00:14:14,878
Hello, Marianne.

214
00:14:14,968 --> 00:14:18,756
What? What?

215
00:14:18,848 --> 00:14:22,363
No, tell him 45
is the absolute top offer.

216
00:14:23,608 --> 00:14:26,122
If he goes somewhere else,
he goes somewhere else.

217
00:14:26,208 --> 00:14:29,757
Stop worrying. Everything's fine.
You're doing a fantastic job.

218
00:14:29,848 --> 00:14:34,046
Have a nice morning, Marianne.
God, that woman's gonna drive me crazy.

219
00:14:34,128 --> 00:14:37,677
Your blood pressure went
from 120 over 90 to 148 over 100.

220
00:14:37,768 --> 00:14:40,202
Since when did you become a nurse?

221
00:14:40,288 --> 00:14:41,721
A little appreciation...

222
00:14:41,808 --> 00:14:44,766
Would you like to go to the doctor's
every 15 minutes?

223
00:14:44,848 --> 00:14:46,361
We gotta change our number.

224
00:14:46,448 --> 00:14:49,520
- I need an office.
- What is the point of having an office?

225
00:14:49,608 --> 00:14:52,406
The point is I spent 40 years
building up this company

226
00:14:52,488 --> 00:14:55,764
and they're crapping it up.
They're children there. Babies.

227
00:14:55,848 --> 00:14:58,442
If I had an office,
I can be there from ten to one,

228
00:14:58,528 --> 00:15:03,204
talk to Marianne, read my manuscripts,
and when I come home, boom, I'm retired.

229
00:15:03,288 --> 00:15:05,483
Then we can be really together.

230
00:15:05,568 --> 00:15:08,958
<i>(Ben)</i> You had three heart attacks.
Is that not enough for you?

231
00:15:09,048 --> 00:15:11,721
- Yeah.
- <i>(chair scrapes)</i>

232
00:15:11,808 --> 00:15:14,038
- I gotta go.
- <i>(Pippa)</i> Bye, sweetheart.

233
00:15:16,888 --> 00:15:18,879
- Love you.
- See you.

234
00:15:20,488 --> 00:15:24,800
- <i>(Ben)</i> Back home.
- <i>(Pippa)</i> OK, sweetheart.

235
00:15:27,368 --> 00:15:29,757
<i>(hammering)</i>

236
00:15:39,448 --> 00:15:41,439
What's happening here?

237
00:15:44,208 --> 00:15:49,885
OK. If I'm losing my marbles,
so be it, but I need proof.

238
00:16:06,048 --> 00:16:09,120
<i>(Pippa) How long</i>
<i>before he loses his mind completely?</i>

239
00:16:17,528 --> 00:16:22,124
- The half-baked son is moving in!
- Wonderful.

240
00:16:22,208 --> 00:16:24,199
<i>(piano music)</i>

241
00:16:25,368 --> 00:16:29,247
<i># After the ball is over</i>

242
00:16:29,328 --> 00:16:33,480
<i># After the break of morn</i>

243
00:16:33,568 --> 00:16:37,846
- <i># After the dancers' leaving</i>
- <i>(man)</i> Pippa!

244
00:16:37,928 --> 00:16:42,001
Glad you could come by.
A little eye candy.

245
00:16:42,088 --> 00:16:44,966
Thank you for having me.
That's for you and Dot.

246
00:16:45,048 --> 00:16:47,926
I... wish you would keep an eye on Dot.

247
00:16:48,008 --> 00:16:52,126
She's having a hard time.
I know she talks to you.

248
00:16:52,208 --> 00:16:56,520
- Well, sure. Erm, where is she?
- He won't come out!

249
00:16:56,608 --> 00:17:00,521
Can you believe it?
A 35-year-old man hiding in his room

250
00:17:00,608 --> 00:17:03,122
when his parents
are throwing a party for him?

251
00:17:03,208 --> 00:17:06,564
I told her this was a bad idea.
He's right down the hall.

252
00:17:06,648 --> 00:17:09,037
- OK.
- Spare bedroom.

253
00:17:09,128 --> 00:17:11,517
Get her to drink a Pepsi Cola
or something.

254
00:17:11,608 --> 00:17:13,883
- OK.
- <i>(man)</i> I'm not going out there!

255
00:17:13,968 --> 00:17:17,802
<i>(Dot)</i> You can go out there for five
minutes. You've got to eat something.

256
00:17:17,888 --> 00:17:20,800
<i>(man)</i> Why are you crying? Stop crying.

257
00:17:20,888 --> 00:17:26,246
- <i>(man)</i> Yeah? Who is it?
- It's Pippa Lee. I'm looking for Dot.

258
00:17:26,328 --> 00:17:28,319
<i>(Dot)</i> Oh, dear.

259
00:17:30,728 --> 00:17:34,084
Erm, hi, Dot.
Johnny asked me to find you.

260
00:17:34,168 --> 00:17:36,523
<i>(Dot)</i> Well, look at me.

261
00:17:36,608 --> 00:17:39,327
- I can't go out there.
- <i>(applause)</i>

262
00:17:40,128 --> 00:17:42,119
I'm Pippa Lee.

263
00:17:43,168 --> 00:17:45,159
Chris.

264
00:17:48,328 --> 00:17:51,047
Oh, why are you putting that on? I...

265
00:17:51,128 --> 00:17:53,722
I ironed you that shirt I got you.

266
00:17:53,808 --> 00:17:56,800
<i>(Chris)</i> Excuse me,
but there's something I need to do.

267
00:17:56,888 --> 00:17:58,879
<i>(Dot)</i> Where are you going?

268
00:18:03,528 --> 00:18:05,564
Where are you?

269
00:18:05,648 --> 00:18:10,768
He was the sweetest little boy.
I mean, you just can't imagine.

270
00:18:10,848 --> 00:18:14,045
When you adopt, you just
don't know what you're gonna get.

271
00:18:15,088 --> 00:18:17,079
<i>(engine starts)</i>

272
00:18:17,168 --> 00:18:21,559
<i>(TV) Look out!</i>
<i>Thank God she didn't fall in.</i>

273
00:18:21,648 --> 00:18:23,718
<i>(Pippa) Amazingly, it took me 16 years</i>

274
00:18:23,808 --> 00:18:26,447
<i>to figure out what was</i>
<i>behind Suky's personality.</i>

275
00:18:27,968 --> 00:18:31,085
- She's taking Dexedrine.
- Who is?

276
00:18:31,168 --> 00:18:33,159
Mom.

277
00:18:34,408 --> 00:18:37,286
- What's Dexedrine?
- Speed.

278
00:18:37,368 --> 00:18:40,007
It's why she never sleeps,
why she acts so weird.

279
00:18:40,088 --> 00:18:42,079
Mom doesn't act weird.

280
00:18:51,328 --> 00:18:53,683
- Mom, why do you take this stuff?
- Hmm?

281
00:18:53,768 --> 00:18:57,238
- These pills. What do you take 'em for?
- It's my medicine.

282
00:18:57,328 --> 00:18:59,364
Can you put it back, please?

283
00:19:02,328 --> 00:19:04,319
Chester told me it was speed.

284
00:19:04,408 --> 00:19:06,638
Chester doesn't know
what he's talking about.

285
00:19:06,728 --> 00:19:12,405
- What happens if you don't take them?
- I'd get fat, like Grandma Sally.

286
00:19:12,488 --> 00:19:17,562
Is that what you want? You all want me
to walk around like some sick walrus?

287
00:19:17,648 --> 00:19:20,685
- No.
- Why don't you just let me do my work?

288
00:19:20,768 --> 00:19:22,804
Better yet, why don't you help me?

289
00:19:22,888 --> 00:19:25,641
Why doesn't anybody around here
help me?

290
00:19:25,728 --> 00:19:28,845
<i>(man)</i> The cross is made of
a vertical and a horizontal beam.

291
00:19:28,928 --> 00:19:32,204
The vertical beam
points to the sky, to the spirit.

292
00:19:32,288 --> 00:19:35,997
The horizontal beam is the line
of the earth, of life on earth.

293
00:19:36,088 --> 00:19:39,364
That's what's neat about Jesus.
He wasn't just the son of God.

294
00:19:39,448 --> 00:19:41,598
I'd like to know
what you're really like.

295
00:19:42,848 --> 00:19:45,920
- What do you mean?
- Without that stuff.

296
00:19:46,008 --> 00:19:51,002
<i>(sighs)</i> Stop being so overdramatic.
You're blowing this out of proportion.

297
00:19:51,088 --> 00:19:55,127
So stop. I don't care if you get fat.

298
00:19:56,288 --> 00:19:58,279
It's my medicine.

299
00:20:04,368 --> 00:20:09,123
OK, fine.
<i>(sighs)</i> Let's just hope I don't blow up.

300
00:20:10,008 --> 00:20:12,238
<i>(father)</i>
Father, thank you for this food,

301
00:20:12,328 --> 00:20:14,603
for the gift of being together
as a family.

302
00:20:14,688 --> 00:20:16,883
For these beautiful children around me.

303
00:20:16,968 --> 00:20:20,517
<i>(Pippa) Suky's cold turkey</i>
<i>lasted exactly one week.</i>

304
00:20:20,608 --> 00:20:23,168
<i>("Little Turtle Dove" by Bobby Day)</i>

305
00:20:25,648 --> 00:20:28,446
- <i>(continues praying)</i>
- Who is the President?

306
00:20:28,528 --> 00:20:30,678
Does anyone know
who the President is?

307
00:20:30,768 --> 00:20:32,838
Boys, it's lawn-mowing day tomorrow.

308
00:20:32,928 --> 00:20:37,046
<i>(Pippa) Imagine a dinner like this</i>
<i>that went on for an entire year.</i>

309
00:20:37,128 --> 00:20:41,565
<i>(father)</i> I know you want to get out
in the woods, but we won't do that...

310
00:20:41,648 --> 00:20:44,481
<i>She was taking</i>
<i>more and more of the stuff.</i>

311
00:20:47,328 --> 00:20:51,082
<i>I never knew who she was gonna be</i>
<i>from one minute to the next.</i>

312
00:20:51,168 --> 00:20:55,639
<i>(father)</i> And I also would like someone
to take care of the gutters.

313
00:20:57,848 --> 00:21:00,999
<i># Can't you hear me calling, calling?</i>

314
00:21:01,088 --> 00:21:02,999
<i># Calling for your love?</i>

315
00:21:03,488 --> 00:21:05,763
<i>(father)</i> Excuse me. Pippa!

316
00:21:21,568 --> 00:21:23,559
<i>(pants)</i>

317
00:21:28,528 --> 00:21:30,519
<i>(music blasts)</i>

318
00:21:38,328 --> 00:21:41,126
- <i>(turns music down)</i>
- What's going on here, miss?

319
00:21:41,208 --> 00:21:44,484
Come dance with me, Mom.
Mommy, dance with me, OK?

320
00:21:44,568 --> 00:21:47,719
- Put your feet on, OK?
- What is going on?

321
00:21:47,808 --> 00:21:51,164
Put your feet on. Come on, remember?
<i>(whimpers)</i>

322
00:21:52,728 --> 00:21:55,037
Mommy, I got a little secret now, OK?

323
00:21:55,128 --> 00:21:59,167
I totally did <i>it. (laughs)</i>

324
00:21:59,248 --> 00:22:01,716
- What? What are you talking about?
- <i>(laughs)</i>

325
00:22:01,808 --> 00:22:05,721
- Huh?
- I'm high, too.

326
00:22:05,808 --> 00:22:09,005
Now we can both be high together, OK?
You and me, Mom.

327
00:22:09,088 --> 00:22:11,761
Oh, you took my medicine.
How much did you take?

328
00:22:11,848 --> 00:22:16,922
I don't know. It's OK, though, Mommy.
I love you. I love you.

329
00:22:17,008 --> 00:22:19,886
Mom, I love you so <i>much. (sobs)</i>

330
00:22:19,968 --> 00:22:22,118
<i>(sobs)</i>

331
00:22:22,928 --> 00:22:25,920
We just can't tell your dad about this,
OK?

332
00:22:27,728 --> 00:22:31,687
- You're OK with this?
- Yeah.

333
00:22:40,328 --> 00:22:42,319
Yeah.

334
00:22:43,408 --> 00:22:47,083
- I am so... sick of you!
- You!

335
00:22:47,168 --> 00:22:50,046
I knew you were bad
from the day you were born!

336
00:22:50,128 --> 00:22:52,164
- You!
- No!

337
00:22:52,888 --> 00:22:55,561
<i>(screams)</i>

338
00:22:55,648 --> 00:22:57,639
<i>(sobs)</i>

339
00:23:01,808 --> 00:23:04,117
<i>(Pippa)</i>
<i>She was never going to back down.</i>

340
00:23:04,208 --> 00:23:08,406
<i>She was never going to change, even if</i>
<i>it meant dragging me down with her.</i>

341
00:23:11,888 --> 00:23:14,277
<i>(dog barks in the distance)</i>

342
00:23:40,848 --> 00:23:45,683
Oh, <i>Herb. (tuts)</i>

343
00:23:50,368 --> 00:23:52,598
<i>(video player clicks)</i>

344
00:24:25,528 --> 00:24:27,644
Herb. Herb. Herb!

345
00:24:28,728 --> 00:24:31,367
- Herb, wake up! It's me.
- What?

346
00:24:31,448 --> 00:24:33,564
- It's me on the video.
- Hold on, kid.

347
00:24:33,648 --> 00:24:37,004
- What are we talking about?
- The chocolate cake and the yogurt.

348
00:24:37,088 --> 00:24:39,204
I just saw it on the video.
It's horrible.

349
00:24:39,288 --> 00:24:41,006
It was you?

350
00:24:41,088 --> 00:24:45,604
I was sitting on the floor,
eating like an <i>animal. (pants)</i>

351
00:24:45,688 --> 00:24:49,567
Herb... I think I'm going insane.

352
00:24:49,648 --> 00:24:53,118
- Maybe I'm going insane.
- Come here.

353
00:24:55,048 --> 00:24:57,516
- <i>(pants)</i>
- Take it easy.

354
00:25:03,048 --> 00:25:06,006
Look at it this way.
Your being a sleepwalker

355
00:25:06,088 --> 00:25:10,127
is a hell of a lot better
than me being senile, isn't it?

356
00:25:10,208 --> 00:25:13,439
- Hmm?
- <i>(sniffs)</i> Of course it is.

357
00:25:14,568 --> 00:25:19,119
Sleepwalkers are a dime a dozen. You'll
never get off a murder rap that way.

358
00:25:19,208 --> 00:25:21,199
<i>(chuckles)</i>

359
00:25:29,168 --> 00:25:32,444
<i>(gasps)</i> Oh, my God.

360
00:26:03,288 --> 00:26:06,007
<i>(man)</i> Pippa Lee, right?

361
00:26:06,088 --> 00:26:08,443
Oh, hello.

362
00:26:08,528 --> 00:26:12,567
- You got a job already.
- I'm working my way to the top.

363
00:26:14,408 --> 00:26:18,526
- It's a beautiful day.
- Trying not to notice.

364
00:26:20,168 --> 00:26:22,921
Oh, and a pack of Marlboro Lights.

365
00:26:24,448 --> 00:26:26,678
- Costly habit.
- I don't really...

366
00:26:26,768 --> 00:26:28,759
I don't smoke, I just, erm...

367
00:26:30,288 --> 00:26:33,678
- You don't work here at night, do you?
- I haven't yet.

368
00:26:34,368 --> 00:26:36,165
Why do you ask?

369
00:26:36,248 --> 00:26:40,321
Oh, I just always thought,
what a horrible job it would be

370
00:26:40,408 --> 00:26:44,083
just waiting for someone
to buy his cigarettes or something.

371
00:26:45,488 --> 00:26:48,958
- Matches?
- Please.

372
00:26:52,568 --> 00:26:57,437
I'm sorry about ducking out on you.
I'm not a big party person.

373
00:26:57,528 --> 00:27:00,122
Oh, no, no, no,
I shouldn't have interrupted.

374
00:27:02,688 --> 00:27:05,486
Erm, actually, I don't need a bag.
That's OK.

375
00:27:05,568 --> 00:27:08,287
And give your mother my best.

376
00:27:12,568 --> 00:27:15,287
<i>(woman)</i>
These strawberries are so sweet.

377
00:27:15,368 --> 00:27:19,759
- These strawberries. So sweet.
- Mm. Maple Bank Farm.

378
00:27:19,848 --> 00:27:24,126
- How's the book coming?
- I'm 100 pages in. Who knows?

379
00:27:24,208 --> 00:27:28,565
- You know.
- How do you know I know?

380
00:27:28,648 --> 00:27:32,527
Cos you always do that. You pretend
it's not gonna work when you know it is.

381
00:27:32,608 --> 00:27:37,284
I have an idea. Why don't you
finish all my conversations for me,

382
00:27:37,368 --> 00:27:40,917
since you know what I'm thinking?
It'll save us all a lot of time.

383
00:27:41,008 --> 00:27:43,124
Well, there's a good idea.

384
00:27:45,648 --> 00:27:49,357
Do bats really get in your hair?

385
00:27:49,448 --> 00:27:53,157
Can you please
just come up with one thing

386
00:27:53,248 --> 00:27:55,808
that isn't a weird little cliché?

387
00:27:55,888 --> 00:27:59,563
<i>(gasps)</i>
I think I left the lights on in the car.

388
00:28:25,408 --> 00:28:28,718
<i>(Pippa) Aunt Trish was</i>
<i>the kindest person I have ever known.</i>

389
00:28:30,608 --> 00:28:32,724
We can talk about it later.

390
00:28:36,648 --> 00:28:38,923
Go get some rest.

391
00:28:48,848 --> 00:28:50,327
Who are you?

392
00:28:55,008 --> 00:28:58,887
I'm Kat. This is my room.

393
00:28:58,968 --> 00:29:00,765
I'm sorry.

394
00:29:00,848 --> 00:29:02,281
No problemo.

395
00:29:04,248 --> 00:29:06,637
<i>(typewriter keys tap)</i>

396
00:29:13,808 --> 00:29:17,084
- <i>(door opens)</i>
- <i>(Trish)</i> Hey. Did you sleep OK?

397
00:29:19,448 --> 00:29:22,599
- Who's Kat?
- Er, she's my roommate.

398
00:29:22,688 --> 00:29:26,203
Listen, your parents
are gonna be here in a few hours.

399
00:29:26,288 --> 00:29:27,277
What?

400
00:29:27,368 --> 00:29:29,757
You have to deal with them
sooner or later.

401
00:29:29,848 --> 00:29:32,203
As far as I'm concerned,
you can stay with me,

402
00:29:32,288 --> 00:29:35,246
so long as you end up
with a high school diploma.

403
00:29:35,328 --> 00:29:37,523
I know there's a problem at your house.

404
00:29:37,608 --> 00:29:40,247
- You do?
- Hm-hmm.

405
00:29:40,328 --> 00:29:45,038
No one else is gonna say it, so I will.
You did good getting away.

406
00:29:48,248 --> 00:29:50,887
Hmm? <i>(chuckles)</i>

407
00:29:50,968 --> 00:29:54,438
- Ta-dah.
- OK, bye.

408
00:29:54,528 --> 00:29:56,996
Bye. Bye.

409
00:30:01,368 --> 00:30:04,485
- See you tonight, Pippa.
- <i>(Pippa)</i> Bye.

410
00:30:05,568 --> 00:30:08,241
- Wow, Aunt Trish.
- <i>(door closes)</i>

411
00:30:09,328 --> 00:30:11,478
We're a couple of black sheep,
you and me.

412
00:30:11,568 --> 00:30:13,559
<i>(both chuckle)</i>

413
00:30:17,288 --> 00:30:19,961
<i>(Pippa)</i> I'm not running away.

414
00:30:20,048 --> 00:30:22,482
I'm just done, that's all.

415
00:30:22,568 --> 00:30:25,287
<i>(father)</i>
But what does that mean, you're done?

416
00:30:27,128 --> 00:30:30,279
It means I don't wanna live with you.

417
00:30:30,368 --> 00:30:33,246
<i>(tuts)</i> Oh, so this is all my fault.

418
00:30:33,328 --> 00:30:36,525
- What's all your fault?
- What you did to me!

419
00:30:37,808 --> 00:30:40,686
- I didn't do anything to you.
- <i>(scoffs)</i>

420
00:30:42,248 --> 00:30:44,557
I'm done. Don't you get it?

421
00:30:44,648 --> 00:30:47,560
You're not even gonna come home
for Christmas any more?

422
00:30:47,648 --> 00:30:52,199
No, I didn't say that. <i>I... (sighs)</i>
Of course I will, Mom.

423
00:30:53,888 --> 00:30:55,879
- <i>(sobs)</i>
- I just...

424
00:30:55,968 --> 00:30:58,846
I think it's better
if I don't live there any more.

425
00:30:58,928 --> 00:31:02,716
<i>(sobs)</i> What... What did I do to you?

426
00:31:04,368 --> 00:31:08,407
What did I do to you to make you
so secretive and unhappy?

427
00:31:09,688 --> 00:31:11,679
Nothing.

428
00:31:13,368 --> 00:31:17,361
- What did I do to you? <i>(sobs)</i>
- Please, Mom.

429
00:31:17,448 --> 00:31:18,847
Please.

430
00:31:22,768 --> 00:31:24,884
Don't be sad.

431
00:31:24,968 --> 00:31:27,880
No, no, you don't be sad, honey, honey.

432
00:31:27,968 --> 00:31:32,086
My baby. It's OK. I love you so much.

433
00:31:32,168 --> 00:31:36,605
