- English and Armenian.

653
00:49:09,528 --> 00:49:14,044
- Ah. Well, welcome.
- <i>(Gigi whoops)</i>

654
00:49:16,848 --> 00:49:22,366
You don't have a bathing suit?
Go naked! Nobody's here! Come on!

655
00:49:22,448 --> 00:49:24,962
Come on!

656
00:49:30,968 --> 00:49:33,084
<i>(chatter)</i>

657
00:49:49,728 --> 00:49:55,200
<i>(Gigi)</i> I'm so happy to see you. I want
to organise a show in Paris for you.

658
00:49:55,288 --> 00:49:57,802
Have you been in Paris before?

659
00:49:59,368 --> 00:50:01,359
<i>(Pippa)</i> That's fantastic.

660
00:50:12,128 --> 00:50:14,119
What's going on?

661
00:50:25,088 --> 00:50:29,798
Pippa. Pippa Sarkissian.
Come here. Come.

662
00:50:31,848 --> 00:50:34,487
Sit. Talk to us.

663
00:50:36,488 --> 00:50:41,881
So, Pippa, what does a free spirit
like you have for breakfast usually?

664
00:50:41,968 --> 00:50:45,324
- Does she look like she eats breakfast?
- Do you?

665
00:50:46,848 --> 00:50:49,282
- No.
- That's your first mistake of the day.

666
00:50:49,368 --> 00:50:52,087
So, first thing in the morning,
you go to the studio?

667
00:50:52,168 --> 00:50:53,965
I don't have a studio.

668
00:50:54,048 --> 00:50:56,323
You gotta be an artist
dressed like that.

669
00:50:56,408 --> 00:50:59,764
- <i>(Herb)</i> Well, what do you do?
- I work in a clothing store.

670
00:50:59,848 --> 00:51:01,804
You have no ambition?

671
00:51:03,728 --> 00:51:07,562
No one has ever walked through that
door before without having an ambition.

672
00:51:07,648 --> 00:51:09,684
The butler is writing a short story.

673
00:51:09,768 --> 00:51:12,805
- He told me so himself yesterday.
- I'm gonna get a drink.

674
00:51:12,888 --> 00:51:14,879
- You want a drink, Pippa?
- Uh-uh.

675
00:51:14,968 --> 00:51:19,200
- Get me another one of these.
- I will. I'll be back.

676
00:51:22,648 --> 00:51:26,004
This is the most amazing house
I've ever seen.

677
00:51:26,088 --> 00:51:28,363
It's not a house, it's a mausoleum.

678
00:51:28,448 --> 00:51:32,680
There isn't one comfortable
piece of furniture except this couch.

679
00:51:32,768 --> 00:51:36,078
- It's like living in an aquarium.
- Then why do you live here?

680
00:51:36,168 --> 00:51:40,923
My wife. I could never afford a place
like this, although I'm not poor.

681
00:51:42,208 --> 00:51:46,486
So, Pippa, when are you going to start
doing something about your life?

682
00:51:46,568 --> 00:51:48,160
What do you mean?

683
00:51:48,248 --> 00:51:50,716
Doesn't it get dispiriting
being so aimless?

684
00:51:50,808 --> 00:51:54,005
I mean, the times,
they are a-changing notwithstanding.

685
00:51:57,888 --> 00:51:59,367
What?

686
00:52:00,768 --> 00:52:03,646
You have such a sweetness about you.

687
00:52:05,488 --> 00:52:08,400
No, I'm not sweet.

688
00:52:08,488 --> 00:52:12,447
Well, you can be experienced
and have a sweetness about you.

689
00:52:12,528 --> 00:52:15,964
It's an innate thing with you, it seems.

690
00:52:18,808 --> 00:52:23,438
I haven't seen that quality in a person
in a long time.

691
00:52:23,528 --> 00:52:25,962
<i>(Gigi)</i> We're all going swimming!

692
00:52:27,968 --> 00:52:29,287
Oh, God.

693
00:52:29,368 --> 00:52:32,804
<i>(Pippa) I didn't realise it yet,</i>
<i>but I had set my sights on Herb,</i>

694
00:52:32,888 --> 00:52:34,879
<i>and once that happened, watch out.</i>

695
00:52:34,968 --> 00:52:38,563
She's making me nostalgic
for his first wife,

696
00:52:38,648 --> 00:52:41,037
and trust me, that's saying something.

697
00:52:42,528 --> 00:52:45,679
You're interesting, Pippa.
I've been observing you.

698
00:52:45,768 --> 00:52:50,637
- You have?
- You're like an ingénue femme fatale.

699
00:52:52,128 --> 00:52:56,121
- OK, and what are you like?
- Writers are vampires.

700
00:52:56,208 --> 00:52:59,678
I'm waiting for the right girl to come
along and make me a human being.

701
00:53:01,328 --> 00:53:04,240
You realise that if I leaned in
right now and kissed you,

702
00:53:04,328 --> 00:53:07,479
I'd be the third guy tonight.
Am I right?

703
00:53:09,048 --> 00:53:11,403
Yeah, you would.

704
00:53:16,528 --> 00:53:18,519
<i>(laughter)</i>

705
00:53:18,608 --> 00:53:22,157
<i>("Another Green World" by Brian Eno)</i>

706
00:53:23,288 --> 00:53:24,607
<i>(laughs)</i>

707
00:53:24,688 --> 00:53:27,521
- Your turn.
- Alright.

708
00:53:30,568 --> 00:53:32,206
Come on!

709
00:53:33,368 --> 00:53:36,166
- There you go. Thanks.
- See you next week.

710
00:53:36,248 --> 00:53:37,727
Next?

711
00:53:40,688 --> 00:53:42,679
Fish tonight?

712
00:53:43,608 --> 00:53:48,682
Oh! Well, he, erm, comes all the way
from Maine every Thursday.

713
00:53:50,128 --> 00:53:53,803
- You feel guilty about the fish man?
- A little.

714
00:53:55,928 --> 00:53:59,364
- I'm sorry about the other day.
- Oh, that's alright.

715
00:54:01,248 --> 00:54:04,524
- How are you doing?
- Oh, fine.

716
00:54:05,688 --> 00:54:09,397
I-I actually went to see someone
about the sleepwalking,

717
00:54:09,488 --> 00:54:13,197
and he basically thinks I'm off my nut,
<i>basically. (laughs)</i>

718
00:54:13,288 --> 00:54:16,086
Erm, see, it's a psychiatrist.

719
00:54:16,168 --> 00:54:19,877
That's because he thinks I'm gonna need
medication, and a locksmith.

720
00:54:19,968 --> 00:54:22,960
He suggested that we bolt
the bedroom door from the inside

721
00:54:23,048 --> 00:54:24,925
and Herb hide the key, and erm...

722
00:54:25,008 --> 00:54:30,128
Oh, I'm supposed to take up a hobby.
I'm thinking <i>bowling. (sighs)</i>

723
00:54:31,648 --> 00:54:34,924
- Would you like to go for a drive?
- <i>(giggles)</i> Sure.

724
00:54:35,008 --> 00:54:37,078
After you get your fish.

725
00:54:38,568 --> 00:54:40,843
I'll make pasta.

726
00:54:41,848 --> 00:54:44,043
Where do you want to go?

727
00:54:46,328 --> 00:54:49,400
I don't <i>know. (chuckles)</i> Erm...

728
00:54:49,488 --> 00:54:53,322
- I could show you where I grew up.
- OK.

729
00:54:56,088 --> 00:54:57,885
How do I get there?

730
00:54:57,968 --> 00:55:03,042
It's straight for a couple of miles.
Then we'll make a turn. I'll tell you.

731
00:55:03,128 --> 00:55:05,437
It's close.

732
00:55:06,008 --> 00:55:07,680
<i>(Pippa)</i> There it is.

733
00:55:15,768 --> 00:55:19,317
- <i>(Pippa)</i> Seems so small.
- Is your family still here?

734
00:55:20,768 --> 00:55:22,759
No.

735
00:55:27,848 --> 00:55:31,079
That's my daughter, Grace. She hates me.

736
00:55:33,448 --> 00:55:35,245
I wonder...

737
00:55:36,528 --> 00:55:39,679
- What?
- If I got it all wrong with her.

738
00:55:41,048 --> 00:55:44,120
I just didn't want to suffocate her
the way my...

739
00:55:46,408 --> 00:55:50,845
I think it happens like that in families
sometimes, though.

740
00:55:50,928 --> 00:55:54,716
You just keep swinging back and forth
from generation to generation,

741
00:55:54,808 --> 00:55:58,198
getting it wrong, the opposite way.

742
00:56:01,568 --> 00:56:03,877
It was so simple with Ben.

743
00:56:06,808 --> 00:56:11,324
But you know, she, erm,
is a photographic journalist.

744
00:56:11,408 --> 00:56:15,447
Travels all over the world, wherever
it's exploding, takes photographs.

745
00:56:15,528 --> 00:56:17,200
- Wow.
- Yeah, I know.

746
00:56:17,288 --> 00:56:19,438
We must have done something right.

747
00:56:22,048 --> 00:56:24,198
Sounds like your daughter's like you.

748
00:56:26,208 --> 00:56:29,917
- Why?
- You said you were always in a drama.

749
00:56:32,608 --> 00:56:35,361
Well, I was reckless with my life,
that's true.

750
00:56:45,208 --> 00:56:47,324
I never saw her again.

751
00:56:49,888 --> 00:56:52,243
- Who?
- My mother.

752
00:56:52,328 --> 00:56:55,718
After I ran away, she died.
She had a heart attack.

753
00:56:58,288 --> 00:57:00,483
<i>(Suky)</i> Oh, I can't wait to see.

754
00:57:02,688 --> 00:57:04,679
<i>(Pippa) If I could have anything,</i>

755
00:57:04,768 --> 00:57:07,680
<i>I would ask for one more afternoon</i>
<i>with my mother.</i>

756
00:57:07,768 --> 00:57:10,043
Look at her eyes.

757
00:57:10,128 --> 00:57:12,278
<i>(Pippa) I would be kind.</i>

758
00:57:12,368 --> 00:57:14,359
Beautiful.

759
00:57:21,608 --> 00:57:23,883
I've been going to Dot's pottery class.

760
00:57:23,968 --> 00:57:28,007
- Oh, good.
- Why do you think it's good?

761
00:57:28,088 --> 00:57:30,807
The doctor said
he thought you could use a hobby.

762
00:57:37,688 --> 00:57:40,805
- Tell me what you like about me.
- Right now?

763
00:57:40,888 --> 00:57:42,879
Yeah.

764
00:57:44,128 --> 00:57:47,120
- You put up with me, for one thing.
- That's it?

765
00:57:47,208 --> 00:57:49,403
Of course not.

766
00:57:51,808 --> 00:57:57,201
Herb, what happened to us? We used to
laugh so much. What happened?

767
00:57:57,288 --> 00:58:00,598
- Can't laugh all the time.
- Well, we have to laugh.

768
00:58:00,688 --> 00:58:02,804
- Or what?
- Or she died for nothing.

769
00:58:02,888 --> 00:58:05,846
- Not that again, OK?
- Why am I not allowed to mention her?

770
00:58:05,928 --> 00:58:09,841
I will not let this marriage turn into
a guilt fest. We have been through this.

771
00:58:09,928 --> 00:58:12,965
She was crazy. You get involved
with somebody like that,

772
00:58:13,048 --> 00:58:16,563
it's like putting your hand
in a blender. Your fingers get bloody.

773
00:58:16,648 --> 00:58:19,401
I just can't take it, I can't take it.
I keep seeing her.

774
00:58:19,488 --> 00:58:21,877
I keep seeing her. I keep...

775
00:58:23,248 --> 00:58:27,036
<i>(sighs)</i> I keep seeing the past.
The past just keeps caving in.

776
00:58:28,208 --> 00:58:32,167
I can't take it any more.
I can't take <i>it. (sobs)</i> I'm sorry.

777
00:58:37,248 --> 00:58:39,921
Maybe you should be taking
antidepressants.

778
00:58:41,168 --> 00:58:43,523
<i>(slams table)</i>

779
00:58:44,568 --> 00:58:46,081
What?

780
00:58:53,368 --> 00:58:56,166
You alright? You want to talk?

781
00:58:56,248 --> 00:58:59,126
My mother used to do this.
She'd suddenly disappear,

782
00:58:59,208 --> 00:59:02,723
and I'd find her on the bed in front of
the TV with toast on her belly.

783
00:59:02,808 --> 00:59:05,447
- That's how she died.
- Yes, I know.

784
00:59:06,848 --> 00:59:09,726
- I have to take your blood pressure.
- No, you don't.

785
00:59:25,008 --> 00:59:28,683
<i>(Pippa) I slept for a week</i>
<i>after the party at Herb's beach house.</i>

786
00:59:31,768 --> 00:59:34,521
<i>Maybe I was trying to avoid</i>
<i>my next boyfriend.</i>

787
00:59:36,848 --> 00:59:40,443
<i>When I woke up, I felt an overwhelming</i>
<i>need to hear Herb's voice.</i>

788
00:59:41,768 --> 00:59:44,726
<i>I missed him so much. It was strange.</i>

789
00:59:46,528 --> 00:59:48,519
<i>(hammer bangs)</i>

790
01:00:22,328 --> 01:00:24,717
- <i>(ringing tone)</i>
- <i>(Herb) Hello?</i>

791
01:00:24,808 --> 01:00:30,201
- Er, Mr Lee? Hi, it's Pippa Sarkissian.
- <i>Pippa!</i>

792
01:00:30,288 --> 01:00:34,804
Hey. I-I was wondering,
do you want to go out to breakfast?

793
01:00:34,888 --> 01:00:40,485
- <i>It's three o'clock in the afternoon.</i>
- I meant tomorrow.

794
01:00:42,728 --> 01:00:46,641
<i>(Pippa) He treated me like a pal</i>
<i>at first. He was avuncular.</i>

795
01:00:46,728 --> 01:00:50,687
<i>He teased me about being a waster.</i>
<i>I called him an old fart.</i>

796
01:00:50,768 --> 01:00:54,920
<i>We would get together every couple of</i>
<i>days and take a walk or eat something.</i>

797
01:00:55,008 --> 01:00:58,921
<i>He gave me reading lists.</i>
<i>He wanted to educate me.</i>

798
01:01:00,408 --> 01:01:03,445
- <i>(Pippa)</i> Hey. Sorry I'm late.
- <i>(Herb)</i> You're always late.

799
01:01:03,528 --> 01:01:06,088
Well, maybe you're always early.
<i>(chuckles)</i>

800
01:01:07,208 --> 01:01:11,599
<i>(Herb)</i> I bought something for you.
Now, you only have to wear this once.

801
01:01:11,688 --> 01:01:14,043
I'll be alone at the beach house
this weekend,

802
01:01:14,128 --> 01:01:17,325
- and I want you to come for lunch.
- <i>(Pippa gasps)</i>

803
01:01:17,408 --> 01:01:20,320
- You weren't supposed to buy this.
- I needed to.

804
01:01:20,408 --> 01:01:25,163
<i>(Pippa) I loved being with Herb.</i>
<i>He made me feel protected.</i>

805
01:01:25,248 --> 01:01:27,079
<i>(Herb) I thought I was a writer.</i>

806
01:01:27,168 --> 01:01:31,207
I thought it was my calling,
but it just wasn't. I, er...

807
01:01:32,528 --> 01:01:34,120
I-I couldn't flow.

808
01:01:34,208 --> 01:01:38,679
I have a very critical nature,
and it kept me from being able to flow.

809
01:01:38,768 --> 01:01:44,001
Then I... was slightly lost for a while.
I had no idea what I was gonna do,

810
01:01:44,088 --> 01:01:48,206
and I had a friend in the publishing
business, and he offered me a job.

811
01:01:48,288 --> 01:01:50,518
- And here I am.
- Hmm.

812
01:01:55,648 --> 01:01:57,798
Tell me what you like about me.

813
01:01:59,968 --> 01:02:04,200
Well, you're not a show-off about it,
but I think you're very intelligent,

814
01:02:04,288 --> 01:02:08,486
and... you're beautiful,
but you're cool about it,

815
01:02:08,568 --> 01:02:11,526
and there's a sadness about you,

816
01:02:11,608 --> 01:02:15,999
and I like that, in moderation.

817
01:02:17,328 --> 01:02:21,844
- I like your jacket.
- And that's it?

818
01:02:22,808 --> 01:02:25,083
<i>(laughs)</i> No.

819
01:02:25,168 --> 01:02:28,080
No, I...

820
01:02:30,088 --> 01:02:32,807
I like your face and your voice...

821
01:02:33,848 --> 01:02:37,158
<i>...and,</i> erm...

822
01:02:37,248 --> 01:02:40,240
- This is gonna sound strange.
- Say it.

823
01:02:41,968 --> 01:02:43,959
It's like, erm...

824
01:02:45,408 --> 01:02:48,320
Like I can feel what you're feeling.

825
01:02:48,408 --> 01:02:53,004
You know, if you feel nervous
or happy or sad, I can feel it.

826
01:02:54,288 --> 01:02:57,007
I-In my body, in my fingers.

827
01:02:58,288 --> 01:03:02,042
- What a remarkable thing.
- Oh.

828
01:03:02,128 --> 01:03:05,484
I'd like you not to feel as if you have
to censor yourself around me.

829
01:03:05,568 --> 01:03:09,766
Tell me something about yourself. Tell
me the most important thing about you.

830
01:03:13,088 --> 01:03:15,238
I'm a fuck-up.

831
01:03:22,808 --> 01:03:26,164
<i>(Pippa) I felt like I was being</i>
<i>rescued from a burning wreck.</i>

832
01:03:26,248 --> 01:03:28,603
If I'm good for anything in the world,

833
01:03:28,688 --> 01:03:31,566
it's for letting you know
how wonderful you are.

834
01:03:34,728 --> 01:03:37,083
You're my true wife, you know?

835
01:03:38,288 --> 01:03:42,406
No, you don't want me.
I only make people sad.

836
01:03:42,488 --> 01:03:44,558
I don't believe that.

837
01:03:47,648 --> 01:03:50,879
<i>(sighs)</i> Anyway, you have a wife.

838
01:03:52,288 --> 01:03:56,998
If I have to live with that lunatic
for another week, I'll hang myself.

839
01:03:57,088 --> 01:04:00,364
For years, I've hoped she'd have
an affair so I can walk out on her,

840
01:04:00,448 --> 01:04:03,997
- but she won't do it, the bitch.
- <i>(laughs)</i>

841
01:04:05,848 --> 01:04:08,203
<i>(electrical whirring)</i>

842
01:04:15,168 --> 01:04:21,084
Mrs Lee still seems unwilling to work
her way up like the rest of us.

843
01:04:22,968 --> 01:04:27,678
- <i>(mutters)</i> Oh, go stick it up your ass.
- What did you say to me?

844
01:04:34,848 --> 01:04:36,725
<i>(young Pippa)</i> I don't understand.

845
01:04:36,808 --> 01:04:39,197
She agrees to divorce
if we have lunch with her?

846
01:04:39,288 --> 01:04:41,961
<i>(Herb)</i> She wants to make the switch
in an elegant way.

847
01:04:42,048 --> 01:04:44,323
<i>(Pippa)</i>
I can't believe you agreed to this!

848
01:04:44,408 --> 01:04:47,081
<i>(Herb)</i>
I owe her this much. Come on, let's go.

849
01:04:47,168 --> 01:04:49,557
Hello, Mr Lee. Nice to see you.
Hello, miss.

850
01:04:49,648 --> 01:04:52,116
- <i>(Herb)</i> Hello, Alphonsa.
- <i>(Gigi)</i> Welcome.

851
01:04:52,208 --> 01:04:55,086
<i>(Herb)</i> Hi, hi. Hello, hello, hello.

852
01:04:59,888 --> 01:05:02,243
- <i>(Sam)</i> Hi.
- Sam! What a pleasant surprise.

853
01:05:02,328 --> 01:05:04,558
<i>(Gigi)</i>
I told Ursa to bring in the champagne.

854
01:05:04,648 --> 01:05:07,242
- Perfect symmetry.
- What?

855
01:05:07,328 --> 01:05:12,118
- Come on.
- She invited me for lunch.

856
01:05:14,048 --> 01:05:16,608
<i>(Sam)</i> Stop! Cheers.

857
01:05:21,128 --> 01:05:26,646
- Oh. You're such a baby.
- <i>(Herb)</i> Thanks.

858
01:05:26,728 --> 01:05:30,277
<i>(Pippa) Let's face it,</i>
<i>I wanted Gigi's life at that moment.</i>

859
01:05:30,368 --> 01:05:32,359
<i>It wasn't the money, exactly.</i>

860
01:05:32,448 --> 01:05:35,360
<i>It was just that the money</i>
<i>made everything seem alright.</i>

861
01:05:35,448 --> 01:05:39,680
<i>It was the opposite of chaos,</i>
<i>of everything I had known up until then.</i>

862
01:05:39,768 --> 01:05:41,759
<i>I wanted to be sheltered at last.</i>

863
01:05:44,848 --> 01:05:48,158
- Madam.
- Lunch is served.

864
01:05:48,248 --> 01:05:49,317
Oh, my.

865
01:05:51,608 --> 01:05:53,041
<i>(Gigi)</i> Pippa?

866
01:05:54,048 --> 01:05:55,527
Herb.

867
01:05:58,408 --> 01:06:01,161
<i>(Gigi)</i> This lunch is in honour
of telling it like it is.

868
01:06:02,128 --> 01:06:04,483
You know how we all eat chops
and hamburgers,

869
01:06:04,568 --> 01:06:07,685
and we don't think of the faces
of who gets killed?

870
01:06:09,168 --> 01:06:12,478
- Anybody here a vegetarian?
- <i>(Gigi)</i> Here's the truth as I see it.

871
01:06:12,568 --> 01:06:17,722
- A pig for a cow. A fair exchange.
- <i>(Sam)</i> And who's who?

872
01:06:18,568 --> 01:06:21,321
- Sorry.
- OK, let's have lunch. Who wants pig?

873
01:06:21,408 --> 01:06:23,842
- First, a toast.
- <i>(Sam)</i> Aw, jeez!

874
01:06:24,808 --> 01:06:26,799
<i>(Gigi)</i> To transformation.

875
01:06:40,328 --> 01:06:41,727
Put the gun down.

876
01:06:43,448 --> 01:06:45,439
Put it down.

877
01:06:47,128 --> 01:06:49,164
Put it down, Gigi.

878
01:06:50,288 --> 01:06:53,007
Isn't it funny how men
always marry women

879
01:06:53,088 --> 01:06:57,366
who are easier and easier to dominate,
until they end up with an imbecile?

880
01:06:57,448 --> 01:07:00,042
Put the gun down.

881
01:07:02,408 --> 01:07:04,399
Put it down.

882
01:07:11,568 --> 01:07:14,002
- Give me the... No!
- <i>(gunshot)</i>

883
01:07:16,448 --> 01:07:18,803
<i>(sobs)</i>

884
01:07:32,288 --> 01:07:35,086
<i>(Pippa) Her image would haunt me</i>
<i>for the rest of my life.</i>

885
01:07:35,168 --> 01:07:37,159
<i>(sobs)</i>

886
01:07:38,568 --> 01:07:41,878
<i>I knew without thinking</i>
<i>that not only would I marry Herb,</i>

887
01:07:41,968 --> 01:07:44,880
<i>I would give myself to him,</i>
<i>like a penitent.</i>

888
01:07:46,128 --> 01:07:48,961
<i>This was my last chance at goodness.</i>

889
01:07:49,048 --> 01:07:52,404
<i>If I fucked this up,</i>
<i>I would be fallen forever.</i>

890
01:07:52,488 --> 01:07:57,278
<i>Every day I tried to be good,</i>
<i>to erase the past.</i>

891
01:07:57,368 --> 01:07:59,802
<i>I stopped getting high.</i>

892
01:07:59,888 --> 01:08:02,686
<i>But I didn't know</i>
<i>how to be this new person.</i>

893
01:08:02,768 --> 01:08:07,080
<i>Like a dancer learning a new routine, I
<i>relied on repetition to teach my brain.</i>

894
01:08:07,168 --> 01:08:09,318
Hello? Hello?

895
01:08:09,408 --> 01:08:11,478
Hello?

896
01:08:11,568 --> 01:08:16,403
<i>It wasn't till I had the babies though</i>
<i>that I really believed my own act.</i>

897
01:08:16,488 --> 01:08:19,924
<i>That was when Pippa Sarkissian</i>
<i>disappeared forever.</i>

898
01:08:21,328 --> 01:08:23,842
<i>That was how I became Pippa Lee.</i>

899
01:08:25,128 --> 01:08:30,805
I got thrown out of pottery class.
I got thrown out of pottery class!

900
01:08:36,608 --> 01:08:39,520
- <i>(Herb)</i> Who is it?
- It's me.

901
01:08:39,608 --> 01:08:41,599
<i>(Herb)</i> I'll be right there.

902
01:08:44,168 --> 01:08:47,524
- Everything OK?
- I got thrown out of pottery class.

903
01:08:47,608 --> 01:08:51,647
- Why?
- I told the teacher to screw off.

904
01:08:51,728 --> 01:08:54,037
Let me get my keys.
We'll get some coffee.

905
01:08:54,128 --> 01:08:57,120
She's a witch. She's...

906
01:08:58,008 --> 01:09:00,761
Why is this towel here, sweetheart?

907
01:09:00,848 --> 01:09:04,158
Were you eating, and you didn't
want to mess up the couch?

908
01:09:04,688 --> 01:09:06,041
No.

909
01:09:08,888 --> 01:09:10,162
What?

910
01:09:30,528 --> 01:09:33,565
- <i>(Sandra moans)</i>
- <i>(Pippa tuts)</i>

911
01:09:37,528 --> 01:09:42,204
- When did this start?
- Sometime after we moved here.

912
01:09:45,088 --> 01:09:50,924
I was hoping it was an affair,
but... it just isn't.

913
01:09:51,008 --> 01:09:55,559
I-I know this has got to be...
dreadful for you.

914
01:09:55,648 --> 01:10:00,324
I... I want you to have all the money.
You deserve everything.

915
01:10:00,408 --> 01:10:04,117
<i>(sighs)</i> Thanks. Erm, well,
are you going to marry her?

916
01:10:04,208 --> 01:10:08,884
Well, at my age, it would be
pretty ridiculous, wouldn't it?

917
01:10:08,968 --> 01:10:12,756
And... I just wanna live.

918
01:10:12,848 --> 01:10:16,727
The past few years, I can feel you
starting to bury me, Pippa.

919
01:10:16,808 --> 01:10:21,279
I can feel the earth in my mouth, almost
as if you're looking forward to it.

920
01:10:21,368 --> 01:10:24,440
- How can you say that?
- I can feel you starting to pity me,

921
01:10:24,528 --> 01:10:28,965
being afraid of me.
You're already mourning. Don't deny it.

922
01:10:29,928 --> 01:10:33,079
I mean, of course, I-I am afraid
of you getting old and dying.

923
01:10:33,168 --> 01:10:35,238
It's normal to be afraid.

924
01:10:35,328 --> 01:10:38,638
Well, I don't want to be normal
or mourned. I am not a ghost!

925
01:10:38,728 --> 01:10:41,561
I wanna live!
Nobody knows when they're gonna die.

926
01:10:41,648 --> 01:10:45,880
You could die tomorrow, and fuck you
for making me feel like an old man!

927
01:10:45,968 --> 01:10:49,643
- But, Herb, you <i>are</i> an old man.
- <i>(clattering)</i>

928
01:10:53,928 --> 01:10:57,967
- <i>(Pippa)</i> Oh, my... Oh, Sandra!
- <i>(Sandra whimpers)</i>

929
01:10:58,848 --> 01:11:00,998
Killing yourself
with a disposable razor.

930
01:11:01,088 --> 01:11:03,602
I don't think
anyone's ever done <i>that</i> before.

931
01:11:04,648 --> 01:11:07,560
She was in despair, you know.
She loves you.

932
01:11:07,648 --> 01:11:10,765
This first-aid kit came in handy,
didn't it?

933
01:11:15,568 --> 01:11:19,083
<i>(Pippa) I had the strangest feeling</i>
<i>walking down those stairs.</i>

934
01:11:19,168 --> 01:11:21,682
<i>I suddenly felt so light,</i>

935
01:11:21,768 --> 01:11:24,680
<i>as if a great weight</i>
<i>had been lifted off of me.</i>

936
01:11:36,288 --> 01:11:39,803
<i>(radio) Remember this moment,</i>
<i>sports fans. Remember where you were.</i>

937
01:11:39,888 --> 01:11:42,527
<i>Pippa Lee rounding the bend,</i>
<i>guilt baton in hand,</i>

938
01:11:42,608 --> 01:11:45,680
<i>coming up on Sandra Dulles,</i>
<i>and the pass is complete!</i>

939
01:11:45,768 --> 01:11:48,521
<i>Pippa Lee has passed</i>
<i>the guilt baton to Sandra Dulles!</i>

940
01:11:48,608 --> 01:11:50,883
<i>I never thought</i>
<i>I'd live to see this moment!</i>

941
01:12:23,368 --> 01:12:25,359
- Hi, there.
- Hi.

942
01:12:27,448 --> 01:12:29,439
<i>(laughs)</i>

943
01:12:35,328 --> 01:12:37,319
What's going on?

944
01:12:39,248 --> 01:12:42,684
My husband has been having an affair
with a good friend of mine.

945
01:12:43,808 --> 01:12:45,799
So...

946
01:12:48,168 --> 01:12:50,841
<i>...it's</i> official.
Nobody needs me any more.

947
01:13:09,848 --> 01:13:12,408
<i>(knock at door)</i>

948
01:13:17,048 --> 01:13:20,961
- Hi, Ma.
- <i>(Pippa)</i> Dot!

949
01:13:21,848 --> 01:13:24,316
- Wait.
- Dot! No, no, no.

950
01:13:24,408 --> 01:13:27,400
Please, I didn't mean to upset you.
I really didn't.

951
01:13:27,488 --> 01:13:30,480
- That man is 35 years old.
- But we haven't done...

952
01:13:30,568 --> 01:13:36,245
And you are whatever you are.
It's none... It's none of my beeswax.

953
01:13:36,328 --> 01:13:39,638
It is just disappointing

954
01:13:39,728 --> 01:13:43,880
when someone turns out not to be
the person you thought they were.

955
01:13:43,968 --> 01:13:45,959
<i>(Chris urinates)</i>

956
01:13:50,528 --> 01:13:52,405
I lost control.

957
01:13:56,288 --> 01:14:00,122
I... I care about you tremendously.

958
01:14:01,288 --> 01:14:06,726
Why don't I feel anything? I mean, it
can't be that I don't love you any more.

959
01:14:06,808 --> 01:14:10,960
- I-I adored you only this morning.
- Maybe you're in shock.

960
01:14:11,048 --> 01:14:15,200
- <i>(sighs)</i> It's all so tired.
- What is?

961
01:14:15,288 --> 01:14:18,997
This whole situation.
Let's just fast-forward to the divorce.

962
01:14:40,848 --> 01:14:42,839
<i>Where... (screams)</i>

963
01:14:46,288 --> 01:14:48,756
Where are they? <i>(gasps)</i>

964
01:14:51,408 --> 01:14:53,797
<i>(monitor beeps)</i>

965
01:14:59,368 --> 01:15:01,359
Where were you going, Mom?

966
01:15:02,968 --> 01:15:05,562
Ben, I really don't see
that that's important.

967
01:15:05,648 --> 01:15:08,606
- I just wanna get everything straight.
- <i>(door opens)</i>

968
01:15:08,688 --> 01:15:10,997
<i>(gasps)</i>

969
01:15:13,368 --> 01:15:17,202
I... I had chest pains.

970
01:15:19,608 --> 01:15:22,168
<i>(sobs)</i> I feel like
the gods are punishing me.

971
01:15:22,248 --> 01:15:25,399
Oh, please stop being such an egomaniac
and drink your tea.

972
01:15:25,488 --> 01:15:28,127
You forgive me, Pippa?

973
01:15:29,368 --> 01:15:33,281
- Forgive her for what?
- <i>Oh... (mumbles)</i> I can't.

974
01:15:34,768 --> 01:15:37,236
Ben, your father and Sandra were...

975
01:15:37,328 --> 01:15:39,762
- They... They're in love.
- <i>(sobs)</i>

976
01:15:39,848 --> 01:15:42,840
- That's why I was leaving.
- What?

977
01:15:42,928 --> 01:15:46,967
I'll jump out the window.
I'm so stupid! I'm stupid!

978
01:15:47,048 --> 01:15:49,562
I'm just so selfish!

979
01:15:49,648 --> 01:15:53,357
I'll jump out the window if you don't
forgive me. I'm so stupid!

980
01:15:53,448 --> 01:15:55,916
I forgive you. Get up.
Get up, please. OK.

981
01:15:58,328 --> 01:16:01,400
- You do not forgive her.
- You're right, I don't.

982
01:16:01,488 --> 01:16:03,922
How could Dad do that to you?

983
01:16:04,008 --> 01:16:07,967
Sweetheart, he... was afraid of dying.

984
01:16:08,048 --> 01:16:10,403
He fell in love.

985
01:16:10,488 --> 01:16:15,846
And I wasn't altogether there either,
as of late, so I don't know.

986
01:16:15,928 --> 01:16:17,441
Do you even care?

987
01:16:20,008 --> 01:16:22,363
How can I compete with that?

988
01:16:27,128 --> 01:16:29,926
- <i>(Grace)</i> Hi. Where is he?
- <i>(Pippa)</i> Oh, sweetheart.

989
01:16:30,008 --> 01:16:32,238
Mrs Lee? You have a phone call.

990
01:16:32,328 --> 01:16:35,764
OK, Ben, will you take her in?
I'll be right back.

991
01:16:35,848 --> 01:16:36,997
Hello?

992
01:16:37,088 --> 01:16:39,318
<i>(Sam) I just want to say,</i>
<i>in all the world,</i>

993
01:16:39,408 --> 01:16:43,003
<i>you are the one person to whom</i>
<i>none of this should be happening.</i>

994
01:16:43,088 --> 01:16:47,923
- Thank you, Sam.
- I also want to say that I love you.

995
01:16:48,008 --> 01:16:50,806
- <i>Me, too.</i>
- I mean, really.

996
01:16:50,888 --> 01:16:52,321
Oh.

997
01:16:55,128 --> 01:16:56,686
- <i>Call you later.</i>
- OK.

998
01:16:56,768 --> 01:16:57,883
- <i>Bye.</i>
- Sam.

999
01:16:57,968 --> 01:16:59,481
<i>Yeah?</i>

1000
01:17:00,488 --> 01:17:04,037
I don't want to make butterflied lamb
any more.

1001
01:17:05,808 --> 01:17:10,165
- <i>Oh.</i>
- Do you see what I'm saying?

1002
01:17:14,928 --> 01:17:17,601
- Why did Ben get to stay?
- I don't know.

1003
01:17:17,688 --> 01:17:19,758
He seemed to want it the most.

1004
01:17:19,848 --> 01:17:24,638
Really? How do you measure that?
Do you have some sort of love-ometer?

1005
01:17:24,728 --> 01:17:26,719
Why don't we go home and rest?

1006
01:17:26,808 --> 01:17:30,960
- Has someone been smoking in here?
- I don't know.

1007
01:17:32,368 --> 01:17:33,960
Yuck.

1008
01:17:35,888 --> 01:17:38,800
- Was it Daddy?
- What?

1009
01:17:38,888 --> 01:17:41,880
- If Daddy's been smoking, then...
- No. No.

1010
01:17:45,008 --> 01:17:48,967
So, his brain is just dead,
it's just completely dead?

1011
01:17:49,048 --> 01:17:53,678
He'll never say anything ever again?
Not one thing?

1012
01:17:54,848 --> 01:17:57,681
That's what the doctors
are telling us, sweetheart.

1013
01:17:59,248 --> 01:18:02,320
You didn't even ask
for a second opinion.

1014
01:18:04,488 --> 01:18:06,479
<i>(engine starts)</i>

1015
01:18:11,808 --> 01:18:14,845
- Gracie, I know, sweetie...
- Goodnight.

1016
01:18:27,288 --> 01:18:29,722
Why did you bother to lie?

1017
01:18:35,848 --> 01:18:38,157
<i>(Grace)</i> Oh, my God, you are smoking.

1018
01:18:38,248 --> 01:18:39,920
I'm quitting soon.

1019
01:18:50,328 --> 01:18:53,843
But I have never seen you smoke
in my whole life.

1020
01:18:53,928 --> 01:18:55,919
I know.

1021
01:19:08,088 --> 01:19:10,443
- <i>(Pippa)</i> Aw.
- <i>(Grace sobs)</i>

1022
01:19:10,528 --> 01:19:13,645
I'm so sorry this had to happen to you.

1023
01:19:13,728 --> 01:19:17,482
I'm not crying because of Daddy.

1024
01:19:17,568 --> 01:19:19,559
<i>(sniffs)</i>

1025
01:19:19,648 --> 01:19:22,924
I'm crying because

1026
01:19:23,008 --> 01:19:27,923
I'm so mean to you, all the time,
and I hate it.

1027
01:19:28,008 --> 01:19:30,442
- Aw.
- And I don't want to be.

1028
01:19:30,528 --> 01:19:34,919
I really, really, really <i>don't. (sobs)</i>

1029
01:19:38,568 --> 01:19:42,163
Sweetheart, it's not your fault.

1030
01:19:42,248 --> 01:19:44,716
There's so many things
you don't know about me.

1031
01:19:44,808 --> 01:19:46,799
No, not yet.

1032
01:19:51,448 --> 01:19:54,679
I want to be your friend,

1033
01:19:54,768 --> 01:19:57,077
because...

1034
01:19:57,168 --> 01:20:00,683
Because... we still have time.

1035
01:20:03,328 --> 01:20:07,526
- I'd be honoured to be your friend.
- No, not honoured.

1036
01:20:07,608 --> 01:20:13,399
- Just happy.
- OK, happy.

1037
01:20:13,488 --> 01:20:16,161
Mom.

1038
01:20:27,368 --> 01:20:29,962
<i>(car approaches)</i>

1039
01:20:39,168 --> 01:20:42,717
I saw your light on.
I wanted to see if you needed anything.

1040
01:20:42,808 --> 01:20:45,038
My mom told me what happened.

1041
01:20:45,128 --> 01:20:48,404
Oh. My son is at the hospital,

1042
01:20:48,488 --> 01:20:50,843
and I'm supposed to be resting,
but I can't.

1043
01:20:53,088 --> 01:20:57,479
I could drive you around a little bit.
Do they have your cell?

1044
01:20:59,168 --> 01:21:02,365
- Don't you have work?
- I'm off till five.

1045
01:21:04,448 --> 01:21:06,484
I could write Grace a note.

1046
01:21:09,928 --> 01:21:11,520
OK.

1047
01:21:24,368 --> 01:21:26,120
<i>(Chris)</i> I'm leaving soon.

1048
01:21:27,728 --> 01:21:30,162
<i>(Pippa)</i> And where will you go?

1049
01:21:30,248 --> 01:21:32,204
Back out west, I guess.

1050
01:21:39,488 --> 01:21:42,002
What do you pray for when you pray?

1051
01:21:43,248 --> 01:21:45,443
For my kids to be happy, I guess.

1052
01:21:46,848 --> 01:21:49,043
And to be good.

1053
01:21:49,768 --> 01:21:52,521
It sounds so childish,
saying it out loud.

1054
01:21:53,848 --> 01:21:58,876
- Do you want to pray for your husband?
- It's hopeless.

1055
01:22:01,368 --> 01:22:06,044
- His brain is dead.
- Not for his brain.

1056
01:22:06,128 --> 01:22:08,119
For his soul.

1057
01:22:09,208 --> 01:22:11,642
- I don't know how to do that.
- Me, neither.

1058
01:22:12,488 --> 01:22:14,285
Let's try.

1059
01:22:25,448 --> 01:22:27,837
<i>(unbuttons shirt)</i>

1060
01:23:26,328 --> 01:23:28,319
<i>(pants)</i>

1061
01:23:45,848 --> 01:23:47,839
<i>(moans)</i>

1062
01:23:59,528 --> 01:24:01,519
<i>(pants)</i>

1063
01:24:05,728 --> 01:24:07,719
<i>(sobs)</i>

1064
01:24:19,408 --> 01:24:20,887
<i>(Pippa)</i> Sorry.

1065
01:25:04,168 --> 01:25:05,965
OK, Herb...

1066
01:25:07,288 --> 01:25:09,279
<i>...I'm</i> gonna let you go.

1067
01:25:14,288 --> 01:25:17,758
I'm sure you're pissed as it is
that I've left you like this so long,

1068
01:25:17,848 --> 01:25:20,078
but we wanted to wait for Grace.

1069
01:25:23,288 --> 01:25:25,279
<i>(sniffs)</i>

1070
01:25:26,128 --> 01:25:28,119
<i>(sighs)</i>

1071
01:25:33,968 --> 01:25:36,243
I love you anyway, you know?

1072
01:25:43,048 --> 01:25:45,357
I'll always love you, you bastard.

1073
01:25:47,448 --> 01:25:49,439
<i>(woman)</i> Are you ready now?

1074
01:26:48,128 --> 01:26:50,483
<i>(Pippa)</i>
<i>OK, it's time to turn the corner.</i>

1075
01:26:50,568 --> 01:26:53,241
<i>I'm going to stay with Ben</i>
<i>and his girlfriend in town.</i>

1076
01:26:53,328 --> 01:26:55,523
I'm gonna find a place near them,

1077
01:26:55,608 --> 01:26:58,998
and I'm gonna wait
to become a grandmother.

1078
01:27:14,048 --> 01:27:16,482
- <i>(gasps)</i>
- <i>(brakes screech)</i>

1079
01:27:36,528 --> 01:27:38,803
<i>(car approaches)</i>

1080
01:27:57,688 --> 01:27:59,679
I'm awake.

1081
01:28:01,248 --> 01:28:03,159
<i>(both chatter)</i>

1082
01:28:06,848 --> 01:28:11,763
- Hi, Momma.
- I'm going on a trip.

1083
01:28:11,848 --> 01:28:13,759
- A trip?
- Yes.

1084
01:28:13,848 --> 01:28:18,126
And I was wondering if you could
call these movers right here,

1085
01:28:18,208 --> 01:28:19,721
and take whatever you want,

1086
01:28:19,808 --> 01:28:23,278
and then tell them to give the rest
to goodwill. That would be great.

1087
01:28:23,368 --> 01:28:25,165
What about the memorial service?

1088
01:28:25,248 --> 01:28:28,320
Right, just call everybody on here
except for Sandra,

1089
01:28:28,408 --> 01:28:30,968
and just call me on my cell
and give me the date.

1090
01:28:31,048 --> 01:28:33,608
And you know what?
What the hell. Invite Sandra.

1091
01:28:33,688 --> 01:28:36,202
Mom, are you actually leaving?

1092
01:28:36,288 --> 01:28:38,927
- I'll be back.
